column9:
I finally got to the final game in the C&C 4 series, spent 10 hours on the Brotherhood campaign, and realized that the only things that remained of the C&C atmosphere were the name, Kane, Tiberium, and some units from the second game. Everything else belongs anywhere but what we're used to calling Command & Conquer. If this was EA's experiment in "let's turn the game on its head," it was a success, but I'm a bit shocked. The reasons for the shock:
- There's no economy here. None at all. They built the SCT, and left Tiberium for unit upgrades. Recruit as many as your army size allows, and it will... well, the strategy is almost always the same in the game, with the exception of a few plot twists in the missions themselves;
- Now, instead of a classic base with buildings, we're given three types of mobile bases called crawlers, focused on offense, defense, and support. Apparently, they initially wanted to separate armored vehicles, infantry, and aircraft, but in the end, only defense lacks a mix of the first and third, not to mention balance;
- They rolled out a rank system based on experience gain, which allows you to use new units and upgrades. It's a peculiar move, but why...;
- Unit upgrades were somehow divided into upgrades based on different types of Tiberium, which you get through enemy drops, and general upgrades that you can learn by collecting Tiberium crystals, simultaneously upending the rank system in the same direction. The end result was so-so;
- The plot is extremely disjointed, much is left unexplained, everything comes in bits and pieces, leaving the player to puzzle out what's happening;
- Terrible localization. Since when did they decide to translate GDI as GDI, I don't know...;
- Graphics.... Honestly, I liked the third game much more in this regard.

In conclusion: itâ€™s worth playing just to see the end of the Tiberium era and forget about it.

